\u003EBone remodelling is a continuous process involving the resorption of old bone and the formation of new bone. This process is essential for maintaining bone strength and mineral homeostasis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOsteoclasts\u003C/strong\u003E secrete cathepsin K, an enzyme that plays a key role in the breakdown of bone matrix during bone resorption. Cathepsin K is particularly effective at degrading collagen, a major component of the bone matrix.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOsteoblasts\u003C/strong\u003E are responsible for bone formation rather than resorption, whilst \u003Cstrong\u003Eosteocytes\u003C/strong\u003E are mature bone cells involved in maintaining bone tissue. \u003Cstrong\u003EChondrocytes\u003C/strong\u003E are involved in cartilage formation and are not involved in bone resorption. \u003Cstrong\u003EFibroblasts\u003C/strong\u003E produce collagen and other fibres in connective tissue but do not participate in bone resorption processes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Cathepsin K is an enzyme secreted by osteoclasts, which are responsible for bone resorption.","Osteoclasts play a crucial role in bone remodelling by breaking down bone tissue.","Cathepsin K is involved in the degradation of collagen in the bone matrix."],"references":["Khurana I, Khurana A, Kowlgi NG. Textbook of Medical Physiology_-E-book. Elsevier Health Sciences; 2019.","Clarke B. Normal bone anatomy and physiology. Clin J Am Soc Nephrol. 2008 Nov;3 Suppl 3(Suppl 3):S131-9.","Florencio-Silva R, Sasso GR, Sasso-Cerri E, Sim\u00f5es MJ, Cerri PS. Biology of Bone Tissue: Structure, Function, and Factors That Influence Bone Cells. Biomed Res Int. 2015;2015:421746.","Cowan PT, Launico MV, Kahai P. Anatomy, Bones. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013.","Hall JE. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2021."]},"relationships":{"